<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910822-0018</DOCNO><DOCID>910822-0018.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Innovo Group Inc.:   Nasco Shareholders Approve   Of Merger in Stock Swap</HL><DATE>08/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   INNO</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)TENNESSEE (TN)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Innovo Group Inc., Sugar Land, Texas, said shareholders ofNasco Inc. approved a merger of the two companies in atax-free exchange.   Under terms of the agreement, Innovo, a maker of canvastote bags, said it will issue 0.4432 new common shares foreach of the 3,255,287 Nasco shares, for a total of 1,442,743Innovo shares. Nasco, based in Springfield, Tenn., marketsschool jackets and gym clothing to schools.</LP><TEXT>   Innovo said it expects the merger to increase the combinedcompanies' profit margin because of lower expenses formarketing and administration. The company said it expects a&quot;particularly strong&quot; fourth quarter but couldn't be morespecific, according to company controller Cindy L. Diller.Innovo reported net income of $668,320, or eight cents ashare, on revenue of $7.2 million in 1990.   Ms. Diller said she wasn't certain Nasco's operations inSpringfield would continue and didn't know what the combinedcompanies would be named. Nasco officials couldn't be reachedfor comment.</TEXT></DOC>